entry.string: Select one or more Cable objects, then press F9 to update the status of all objects to Abandoned.

With the first pointing, identify any feature with an annotation field that has not yet been set. As you drag over a candidate, it will be highlighted.
With the second pointing, identify the position for the annotation. Press the shift key while dragging to rotate.
Annotation is added with a justification of 13 (bottom center).

With the first pointing, identify any feature with an annotation field that has not yet been set. As you drag over a candidate, it will be highlighted.
With the second pointing, identify the position for the annotation. Press the shift key while dragging to rotate.

Point to the desired position of the new vertex on a chain or area geometry. Note: if you have selected any geometries in the map, this will only snap to any of those selected geometries. Otherwise, it will snap to any chain or area.
After the new vertex is placed, you will automatically be placed in Move Vertex mode.

Place a trail to define the route of the busbar. Press F9 when complete.
Note that this feature can only be placed in a substation internals map view.
Place a trail to define the route of the cable. Press F9 when complete.
Place a trail to define the route of the cadastral boundary. Press F9 when complete.
Point to the location for the car park.

Place a trail to define the route of the footpath. Press F9 when complete.
Annotation will be placed at the midpoint, with a justification of 13 (bottom center).
Place a trail to define the route of the footpath. Press F9 when complete.
Point to the location for the hotel. Annotation will be added a fixed distance from the location. Press the shift key while dragging to rotate.

Point to the location for the hotel. After placing the hotel, the next pointing will place annotation for the hotel. While dragging: - Hold the shift key to rotate. - Press escape to cancel annotation placement.
Point to the location for the hotel.

Place a trail to define the route of the internal cable. Press F9 when complete.
Note that this feature can only be placed in a substation internals map view.
Point to the location for the joint.
Point to the location for the level crossing.

Make two pointings to identify the two chains which are to be extended. Each pointing should be near the endpoint of the chain that is to be adjusted.
After the second pointing is done, a preview of the proposed line extend results will be drawn. If this preview is acceptable, then either press F9 to complete the operation, or point near the proposed intersection point. If it is not acceptable, then make a pointing at least 50 pixels away from the proposed intersection point, and the operation will be cancelled.
Make two pointings: the first pointing identifies the chain to be trimmed or extended, and the second pointing identifies the chain or area that the first chain should be trimmed or extended to.
Place a trail to define the route of the road. Press F9 when complete.
Place a trail to define the route of the motorway. Press F9 when complete.

If you have selected a geometry (or set of geometries), this tool will move those geometries. Otherwise, it will move the geometry that is correlated where you first press the mouse button.
Press and drag to move the geometry to its new position. Hold down the Shift key while dragging to rotate the data.
Move and rotate set (with manifold interactions)

If you have selected a geometry (or set of geometries), this tool will move those geometries. Otherwise, it will move the geometry that is correlated where you first press the mouse button.
Press and drag to move the geometry to its new position. Hold down the Shift key while dragging to rotate the data.
Upon completion, manifold interactions will be re-run for all data. This means that if you drag one feature on top of another feature that it would normally connect to, then these features will now be connected.

Point to the vertex of a chain or area geometry. Note: if you have selected a chain or area geometry in the map, this will only snap to that selected geometry. Otherwise, it will snap to any chain or area.
Drag the vertex to the desired location, and then release the mouse button to complete this operation.

Place a trail to define the extent of the work point. Press F9 when complete.
Note that this pointing rule does not activate a separate menu for prompting for attributes - enter the attributes directly on the "Custom" tab.
Multi Work Point (multiple points, multiple spans)

Place a trail to define the location of each work point. Press F9 when complete. In addition to work points at each trail point, a work span will be created between each work point.
Note that this pointing rule does not activate a separate menu for prompting for attributes - enter the attributes directly on the "Custom" tab.
Multi Work Point (multiple points, no spans)

Place a trail to define the location of each work point. Press F9 when complete.
Note that this pointing rule does not activate a separate menu for prompting for attributes - enter the attributes directly on the "Custom" tab.
Multi Work Point (multiple points, single span)

Place a trail to define the location of each work point. Press F9 when complete. In addition to work points at each trail point, a work span will be created between the first and last point.
Note that this pointing rule does not activate a separate menu for prompting for attributes - enter the attributes directly on the "Custom" tab.
Multi Work Point (no points, multiple spans)

Place a trail to define the location of each work span. Press F9 when complete. A work span will be created between each trail point.
Note that this pointing rule does not activate a separate menu for prompting for attributes - enter the attributes directly on the "Custom" tab.

Point to the location for the work point. Annotation will be added a fixed distance from the location. Press the shift key while dragging to rotate.
Note that this pointing rule does not activate a separate menu for prompting for attributes - enter the attributes directly on the "Custom" tab.

Place a trail to define the route of the work point. Press F9 when complete.
Note that this pointing rule does not activate a separate menu for prompting for attributes - enter the attributes directly on the "Custom" tab.
Point to the location for the office. This compound pointing rules creates a company and an office at the same time.
Place a trail to define the extent of the park. Press F9 when complete.
Place of Interest (add location to existing coverage)

With the first pointing, identify the coverage geometry of the place of interest to add a location geometry to. As you drag over a candidate, it will be highlighted.
With the second pointing, identify the position for the location. Press the shift key while dragging to rotate.
Place a trail to define the extent of the park. Press F9 when complete.
Point to the location for the place of interest
Point to the location for the pub/restaurant. While dragging: - Press F6 to add an associated access road
Point and drag to identify features. While dragging: - Press F6 to identify the pub/restaurant - Press F7 to identify the car park
Place a trail to define the route of the railway line. Press F9 when complete.

Point to the vertex to be removed. Note: if you have selected any geometries in the map, this will only snap to any of those selected geometries. Otherwise, it will snap to any chain or area.
As you drag, the vertex to be removed is highlighted with a red circle. Release the mouse button to complete this operation.
Road annotation: while dragging, press F6 to select the road to annotate.
Road annotation: while dragging, press F6 to select the road to annotate.

Place a trail to define the route of the road. Press F9 when complete. The following features will be added at the same time: - First point: place of interest - Midpoint: road annotation, with 23 (bottom center) justification - Last point: pub/restaurant

Place a trail to define the route of the road. Press F9 when complete.
At each point, you will be prompted to place a roundabout. If you do not want to place a roundabout at a given location, press cancel on the attribute prompter.
Point to the location for the road works.

With the first pointing, point to the road works object that will be the parent to the road works being placed.
With the second pointing, point to the location for the child road works.
Point to the location for the roundabout. Annotation will be added a fixed distance from the location. Press the shift key while dragging to rotate.

Point to the location for the roundabout. Annotation will be added a fixed distance from the location. Press the shift key while dragging to rotate.
Note that this pointing rule does not activate a separate menu for prompting for attributes - enter the attributes directly on the "Custom" tab.
Point to the location for the shop.
Place a trail to define the route of the slip road. Press F9 when complete.
Point to the chain to be split. The position where you release the mouse defines the split point.

Place a trail to define the extent of the substation. Press F9 when complete.
After placing the substation, the next pointing will place annotation for the substation. While dragging: - Hold the shift key to rotate. - Press escape to cancel annotation placement.

With the first pointing, point to the location for the internal pin - this must be in a substation internals map view. With the second pointing, point to the location for the external pin - this must be in the geographic view.
Point to the location for the supply point. A customer will be added to this supply point automatically.

With the first pointing, point to the location for the primary connection. With the second pointing, point to the location for the secondary connection.
Note that this feature can only be placed in a substation internals map view.

Place a trail to define the extent of the town. Press F9 when complete.
The location and annotation geometry will be placed at the center of the coverage bounds.

With the first pointing, point to the location for the primary connection. With the second pointing, point to the location for the secondary connection.
Note that this feature can only be placed in a substation internals map view.
Place a trail to define the route of the trunk road. Press F9 when complete.
